subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis. This new species resembles
O. hamatus ( Wang, Zhang & Zhang, 2012 )
by having a similarly shaped DTA, short sperm duct, embolus and small spermathecae (see Figs 13A–B , 14A–B and fig. 9E–F in
Wang et al . 2012
), but the male can be distinguished by the wide, dagger-shaped RTA, without a hook at the apex in retrolateral view ( vs thin, with a small hook at the tip of the RTA, compare Figs 13B , 14B with figs 8C, 9F in
Wang et al. 2012
), and the short and thin conductor ( vs wide and long conductor, compare Figs 13C , 14C with figs 8B, 9G in
Wang et al. 2012
). Females can be distinguished by the short and wide median septum ( vs narrow, compare Fig. 14E with fig. 8D in
Wang et al. 2012
) and the two horn-shaped copulatory openings ( vs coalescent copulatory openings, compare Fig. 14E–F with fig. 8D–E in
Wang et al . 2012
).
